# 2️⃣ const Keyword

---

# First Understand the Problem

Suppose:

```cpp
int age = 20;
```

What if we want to prevent accidental changes?

---

# Solution

Use:

```cpp
const int age = 20;
```

---

Now:

```cpp
age = 30;
```

❌ Error

---

# Mental Model

Think:

```text
const = Permanent Marker
```

Once written:

```text
Cannot be changed
```

---

# Why const Exists

To protect important data.

Example:

```text
PI = 3.14159
```

Should not change.

---

## Example

```cpp
const float PI = 3.14159;
```

---

# Real-World Example

Think of:

```text
Date of Birth
```

It doesn't change.

Perfect candidate for const.

---

# const with Functions

Interviewers LOVE this.

---

Suppose:

```cpp
void print(vector<int> v)
```

Entire vector gets copied.

Expensive.

---

Better:

```cpp
void print(const vector<int>& v)
```

---

Let's understand this fully.

---

# Breaking It Down

```cpp
const vector<int>& v
```

Three things happen:

---

### `&`

No copy created.

Uses original vector.

Fast.

---

### `const`

Function cannot modify vector.

Safe.

---

### Result

```text
Fast + Safe
```

This is how professional C++ code is written.

---

# Example

```cpp
void print(const vector<int>& v)
{
    for(int x : v)
    {
        cout << x << " ";
    }
}
```

---

# Why Interviewers Ask This

Because:

```text
Pass by Value
```

copies data.

But:

```text
const reference
```

avoids copying.

Much better performance.

---

# Mental Model

```text
const reference
=
Read Only Access Pass
```

You can see data.

You cannot change it.

---

# Common Interview Question 🔥

Which is better?

```cpp
vector<int> v
```

OR

```cpp
const vector<int>& v
```

Answer:

```cpp
const vector<int>& v
```

Why?

```text
No Copy + Safe Access
```

---

# Quick Comparison

| Method       | Copy? | Modify?               |
| ------------ | ----- | --------------------- |
| int x        | Yes   | No effect on original |
| int &x       | No    | Yes                   |
| const int &x | No    | Cannot modify         |

---

# Real-World Analogy

Imagine a library book.

### Pass by Value

```text
Photocopy entire book
```

Slow.

---

### Reference

```text
Use original book
```

Fast.

---

### const Reference

```text
Use original book
But read only
```

Fast + Safe.

---

